09\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=June 4, 2019}}</ref>\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref name=\"DecennialCensus\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial-census.html|title=Census of Population and Housing|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 4, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\nPort Heiden first appeared on the 1880 U.S. Census as the unincorporated Aleut village of \"Mashikh.\"<ref>{{cite book|title=Geological Survey Professional Paper|url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_yCYlAQAAIAAJ|year=1949|publisher=U.S. Government Printing Office|pages=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_yCYlAQAAIAAJ/page/n62 49]\u2013}}</ref> Some maps erroneously placed it at the latter settlement of Port Moller instead of at Port Heiden. In 1890, it returned as \"Meshik.\" It next reported in 1920 as Port Heiden, and again in 1930. It did not appear again until 1960, but has appeared in every subsequent census. It formally incorporated in 1972.\n\nAs of the census<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2008-01-31|title=U.S. Census website}}</ref> of 2000, there were 119 people, 41 households, and 23 families residing in the city. The population density was 2.3 people per square mile (0.9/km\u00b2). There were 56 housing units at an average density of 1.1 per square&nbsp;mile (0.4/km\u00b2). The racial makeup of the city was 19.33% [[Race (United States Census)|White]], 65.55% [[Race (United States Census)|Native American]], 2.52% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 12.61% from two or more races. 2.52% of the population were [[Race (United States Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Race (United States Census)|Latino]] of any race.\n\nThere were 41 households out of which 39.0% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 46.3% were married couples living together, 2.4% had a female householder with no husband present, and 41.5% were non-families. 39.0% of all households were made up of individuals and 7.3% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.90 and the average family size was 3.79.\n\nIn the city, the age distribution of the population shows 39.5% under the age of 18, 5.0% from 18 to 24, 26.9% from 25 to 44, 22.7% from 45 to 64, and 5.9% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 33 years. For every 100 females, there were 105.2 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 125.0 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the city was $31,875, and the median income for a family was $70,000. Males had a median income of $53,750 versus $21,667 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the city was $20,532. There were no families and 5.6% of the population living below the [[poverty line]], including no under eighteens and 25.0% of those over 64.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Lake and Peninsula Borough, Alaska}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Cities in Alaska]]\n[[Category:Cities in Lake and Peninsula Borough, Alaska]]\n[[Category:Populated coastal places in Alaska]]\n", "name_user": "Menchi", "label": "safe", "comment": "transliterationtags", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Port_Heiden,_Alaska"}
{"title_page": "Bernard Stalter", "text_new": "{{short description|French entrepreneur and politician}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name          = Bernard Stalter\n| image         = Bernard_Stalter.jpg\n| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption       = Stalter in 2018\n| office        = [[Regional Council of Grand Est|Regional Councillor of Grand Est]] for [[Bas-Rhin]]\n| term_start    = 1 January 2016\n| term_end      = 13 April 2020\n| predecessor   = \n| successor     =\n| office2       = Member of the [[French Economic, Social and Environmental Council]]\n| term_start2   = 2015\n| term_end2     = 2018\n| predecessor2  =\n| successor2    =\n| birth_name    = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date    = 12 March 1957\n| birth_place   = [[Brumath]], [[France]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|df=y|2020|04|13|1957|03|12}}\n| death_place   = [[Strasbourg]], France\n| nationality   = [[French people|French]]\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = Politician <br/> Entrepreneur\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}\n\n'''Bernard Stalter''' (12 March 1957 \u2013 13 April 2020) was a French entrepreneur and politician.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dna.fr/economie/2020/04/13/le-leader-de-l-artisanat-bernard-stalter-s-est-eteint|title=Le leader de l\u2019artisanat Bernard Stalter s\u2019est \u00e9teint|date=13 April 2020|work=Derni\u00e8res Nouvelles D'Alsace|language=French}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nStalter was born on 12 March 1957 in [[Brumath]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presseagence.fr/lettre-economique-politique-paca/2016/12/20/paris-bernard-stalter-elu-a-la-presidence-de-lapcma/|title=PARIS : Bernard STALTER, \u00e9lu \u00e0 la pr\u00e9sidence de l\u2019APCMA|date=20 December 2016|work=Presse Agence|language=French}}</ref> At age 14, he began a hairdressing apprenticeship.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lejournaldesentreprises.com/alsace/article/bernard-stalter-le-philanthrope-43114|title=Bernard Stalter : Le philanthrope|date=4 December 2009|work=Le Journal des Entreprises|language=French}}</ref> After he became a certified hairdresser,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.petitesaffiches.fr/nominations,079/bernard-stalter-president-de-l,7978.html|title=Bernard Stalter pr\u00e9sident de l\u2019APCMA|date=20 December 2016|work=Petites Affiches|language=French}}</ref> he worked for the [[French Army]] at the Entzheim Air Base. He opened his first salon in Brumath in 1993.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lesechos.fr/2014/05/bernard-stalter-a-la-tete-des-170000-coiffeurs-de-france-1102392|title=Bernard Stalter \u00e0 la t\u00eate des 170.000 coiffeurs de France|date=26 May 2014|work=Les Echos|language=French}}</ref>\n\nStalter was elected Chair of the Conseil Economique et Social d'Alsace in November 2007, succeeding Jean-Marie Sander. He resigned in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.letelegramme.fr/ar/viewarticle1024.php?aaaammjj=20071207&article=2003472&type=ar|title=Bernard Stalter. Pr\u00e9sident du Cesa|date=7 December 2007|work=Le T\u00e9l\u00e9gramme|language=French}}</ref> In 2014, he became President of the Union Nationale des Entreprises de Coiffure.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lopinion.fr/edition/economie/bernard-stalter-ambassadeur-d-artisanat-qui-revendique-toute-place-136135|title=Bernard Stalter, ambassadeur d\u2019un artisanat qui revendique toute sa place|date=18 October 2017|work=L'Opinion|language=French}}</ref> He was a part of the [[Union Nationale des Entreprises de Coiffure]] from 2015 to 2018. He was President of Beaute Diffusion Events, which earned \u20ac1,468,397 in 2015. He was also an agent for Sarl la Coiffure, Coiffure Bernard, and Agiprim.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dirigeants.bfmtv.com/Bernard-STALTER-3732363/|title=Bernard STALTER|work=BFM Business|language=French}}</ref>\n\nThe only candidate, Stalter was elected to the Alsace and Grand Est Chamber of Trades in November 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.liberation-champagne.fr/art/594889/article/2016-11-17/bernard-stalter-elu-president-de-la-chambre-regionale-des-metiers|title=Bernard Stalter \u00e9lu pr\u00e9sident de la chambre r\u00e9gionale des m\u00e9tiers|date=17 November 2016|work=Lib\u00e9ration Champagne|language=French}}</ref> He was also President of the company Siagi and the Union des corporations artisanales du Bas-Rhin.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lunion.fr/art/6619/article/2016-12-15/l-aslacien-bernard-stalter-president-des-artisans-de-france|title=Les multiples casquettes de l\u2019Alsacien Bernard Stalter pr\u00e9sident, entre autres, des artisans de France|date=18 December 2016|work=L'Union|language=French}}</ref> The following month, he was elected President of CMA France,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lalsace.fr/actualite/2016/12/14/bernard-stalter-elu-president-de-l-apcma|title=Bernard Stalter \u00e9lu pr\u00e9sident de l\u2019APCMA|date=14 December 2016|work=L'Alsace|language=French}}</ref> earning 106 out of the 113 votes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dna.fr/economie/2016/12/13/bernard-stalter-elu-president-de-l-apcma|title=Bernard Stalter \u00e9lu pr\u00e9sident de l\u2019APCMA|date=13 December 2016|work=Derni\u00e8res Nouvelles D'Alsace|language=French}}</ref>\n\nStalter arrived in [[Corsica]] in May 2017 to visit those affected by the floods of November 2016. Many residents of the island received funds from CMA France's disaster management fund.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.corsematin.com/articles/le-chef-des-artisans-rend-visite-aux-sinistres-de-novembre-72646|title=Le chef des artisans rend visite aux sinistr\u00e9s de novembre|date=11 May 2017|work=Corse Matin|language=French}}</ref> He also visited those in [[Guadeloupe]] affected by [[Hurricane Maria]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.guadeloupe.franceantilles.fr/actualite/economie/belle-solidarite-du-monde-de-l-artisanat-451747.php|title=Belle solidarit\u00e9 du monde de l'artisanat|date=6 October 2017|work=FA Guadeloupe|language=French}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2017, he was elected Vice-President of the [[European Association of Craft, Small and Medium-Sized Enterprises]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lefigaro.fr/decideurs/nomination/2018/02/16/33002-20180216ARTFIG00369-bernard-stalter-de-l-alsace-a-l-europe-il-plaide-pour-les-artisans.php|title=Bernard Stalter : de l'Alsace \u00e0 l'Europe, il plaide pour les artisans|date=16 February 2018|work=Le Figaro|language=French}}</ref> He was also elected head of the National Confederation of Handicrafts in Service and Manufacturing Trades on 26 September 2018, succeeding Pierre Martin.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lemondedesartisans.fr/national/fil-infos/bernard-stalter-elu-president-de-la-cnams|title=Bernard Stalter \u00e9lu pr\u00e9sident de la CNAMS|date=26 September 2018|work=artisans.fr|language=French}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 March 2020, Stalter announced on his [[Facebook]] page that he had been diagnosed with [[COVID-19]]. He died on 13 April in [[Strasbourg]] at the age of 63.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.francebleu.fr/infos/sante-sciences/coronavirus-bernard-stalter-president-de-la-chambre-des-metiers-d-alsace-et-de-france-est-mort-1586796552|title=Coronavirus : Bernard Stalter, pr\u00e9sident de la chambre des m\u00e9tiers d'Alsace et de France, est mort|date=13 April 2020|work=France Bleu|language=French}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n*Knight of the [[Ordre national du M\u00e9rite]] (2007)\n*Knight of the [[Legion of Honour]] (2009)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lemondedesartisans.fr/actualites/bernard-stalter-elu-president-de-lapcma|title=Bernard Stalter \u00e9lu pr\u00e9sident de l'APCMA|date=13 December 2016|work=artisans.fr|language=French}}</ref>\n*Officer of the Ordre national du M\u00e9rite (2016)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/affichTexte.do?cidTexte=JORFTEXT000033385452|title=D\u00e9cret du 14 novembre 2016 portant promotion et nomination|date=15 November 2016|work=Legifrance.gouv.fr|language=French}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stalter, Bernard}}\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:French hairdressers]]\n[[Category:21st-century French politicians]]\n[[Category:Chevaliers of the L\u00e9gion d'honneur]]\n[[Category:Officers of the National Order of Merit (France)]]\n[[Category:People from Brumath]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in France]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|French entrepreneur and politician}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name          = Bernard Stalter\n| image         = Bernard_Stalter.jpg\n| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption       = Stalter in 2018\n| office        = [[Regional Council of Grand Est|Regional Councillor of Grand Est]] for [[Bas-Rhin]]\n| term_start    = 1 January 2016\n| term_end      = 13 April 2020\n| predecessor   = \n| successor     =\n| office2       = Member of the [[French Economic, Social and Environmental Council]]\n| term_start2   = 2015\n| term_end2     = 2018\n| predecessor2  =\n| successor2    =\n| birth_name    = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date    = 12 March 1957\n| birth_place   = [[Brumath]], [[France]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|df=y|2020|04|13|1957|03|12}}\n| death_place   = [[Strasbourg]], France\n| nationality   = [[French people|French]]\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = Politician <br/> Entrepreneur\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}\n\n'''Bernard Stalter''' (12 March 1957 \u2013 13 April 2020) was a French entrepreneur and politician.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dna.fr/economie/2020/04/13/le-leader-de-l-artisanat-bernard-stalter-s-est-eteint|title=Le leader de l\u2019artisanat Bernard Stalter s\u2019est \u00e9teint|date=13 April 2020|work=Derni\u00e8res Nouvelles D'Alsace|language=French}}</ref>\n==Biography==\nStalter was born on 12 March 1957 in [[Brumath]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presseagence.fr/lettre-economique-politique-paca/2016/12/20/paris-bernard-stalter-elu-a-la-presidence-de-lapcma/|title=PARIS : Bernard STALTER, \u00e9lu \u00e0 la pr\u00e9sidence de l\u2019APCMA|date=20 December 2016|work=Presse Agence|language=French}}</ref> At age 14, he began a hairdressing apprenticeship.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lejournaldesentreprises.com/alsace/article/bernard-stalter-le-philanthrope-43114|title=Bernard Stalter : Le philanthrope|date=4 December 2009|work=Le Journal des Entreprises|language=French}}</ref> After he became a certified hairdresser,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.petitesaffiches.fr/nominations,079/bernard-stalter-president-de-l,7978.html|title=Bernard Stalter pr\u00e9sident de l\u2019APCMA|date=20 December 2016|work=Petites Affiches|language=French}}</ref> he worked for the [[French Army]] at the Entzheim Air Base. He opened his first salon in Brumath in 1993.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lesechos.fr/2014/05/bernard-stalter-a-la-tete-des-170000-coiffeurs-de-france-1102392|title=Bernard Stalter \u00e0 la t\u00eate des 170.000 coiffeurs de France|date=26 May 2014|work=Les Echos|language=French}}</ref>\n\nStalter was elected Chair of the Conseil Economique et Social d'Alsace in November 2007, succeeding Jean-Marie Sander. He resigned in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.letelegramme.fr/ar/viewarticle1024.php?aaaammjj=20071207&article=2003472&type=ar|title=Bernard Stalter. Pr\u00e9sident du Cesa|date=7 December 2007|work=Le T\u00e9l\u00e9gramme|language=French}}</ref> In 2014, he became President of the Union Nationale des Entreprises de Coiffure.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lopinion.fr/edition/economie/bernard-stalter-ambassadeur-d-artisanat-qui-revendique-toute-place-136135|title=Bernard Stalter, ambassadeur d\u2019un artisanat qui revendique toute sa place|date=18 October 2017|work=L'Opinion|language=French}}</ref> He was a part of the [[Union Nationale des Entreprises de Coiffure]] from 2015 to 2018. He was President of Beaute Diffusion Events, which earned 1,468,397\u20ac in 2015. He was also an agent for Sarl la Coiffure, Coiffure Bernard, and Agiprim.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dirigeants.bfmtv.com/Bernard-STALTER-3732363/|title=Bernard STALTER|work=BFM Business|language=French}}</ref>\n\nThe only candidate, Stalter was elected to the Alsace and Grand Est Chamber of Trades in November 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.liberation-champagne.fr/art/594889/article/2016-11-17/bernard-stalter-elu-president-de-la-chambre-regionale-des-metiers|title=Bernard Stalter \u00e9lu pr\u00e9sident de la chambre r\u00e9gionale des m\u00e9tiers|date=17 November 2016|work=Lib\u00e9ration Champagne|language=French}}</ref> He was also President of the company Siagi and the Union des corporations artisanales du Bas-Rhin.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lunion.fr/art/6619/article/2016-12-15/l-aslacien-bernard-stalter-president-des-artisans-de-france|title=Les multiples casquettes de l\u2019Alsacien Bernard Stalter pr\u00e9sident, entre autres, des artisans de France|date=18 December 2016|work=L'Union|language=French}}</ref> The following month, he was elected President of CMA France,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lalsace.fr/actualite/2016/12/14/bernard-stalter-elu-president-de-l-apcma|title=Bernard Stalter \u00e9lu pr\u00e9sident de l\u2019APCMA|date=14 December 2016|work=L'Alsace|language=French}}</ref> earning 106 out of the 113 votes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dna.fr/economie/2016/12/13/bernard-stalter-elu-president-de-l-apcma|title=Bernard Stalter \u00e9lu pr\u00e9sident de l\u2019APCMA|date=13 December 2016|work=Derni\u00e8res Nouvelles D'Alsace|language=French}}</ref>\n\nStalter arrived in [[Corsica]] in May 2017 to visit those affected by the floods of November 2016. Many residents of the island received funds from CMA France's disaster management fund.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.corsematin.com/articles/le-chef-des-artisans-rend-visite-aux-sinistres-de-novembre